DENGUE - AUSTRALIA (QUEENSLAND)
*******************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Dengue - Australia & South Pacific 971028140721
Dengue - Australia (Torres Strait Islands) 970203104016
Dengue - Australia (Torres Strait Islands) (02) 970426164136
Date: Tue, 16 Dec 1997 06:57:56 WST
From: Denis Green <snoigel@hotmail.com>
Source: Media reports

More than 1000 north Queensland residents are at risk of a deadly form of
dengue fever after a new outbreak of the virus in Cairns.
Cairns City Council began fumigating every house along the city's Esplanade
- the waterfront area where people are believed to be most at risk. Health
authorities also declared a dengue fever watch from Mackay to the Torres
Strait.
Thirteen confirmed or suspected cases have been recorded since Wednesday.
Health authorities fear the disease could be spreading quickly because it
was first reported by staff at a backpackers' hostel.
Tropical Public Health Unit entomologist Scott Ritchie said most of the
hostel workers and guests had been traced but the whereabouts of some were
still unknown.
A spokesman said the latest outbreak was caused by a new variety of dengue-3
virus. "That concerns us greatly because the last one was type 2. When you
get people being infected sequentially by two different strains they can
develop dengue haemorrhagic fever," he said.
Most people [recover from dengue with no sequelae, but those who develop
haemorrhagic fever suffer serious illness and can die.
"What we have done to control this is declare a dengue watch over urban
north Queensland from Mackay to Torres Strait.
We've also declared a dengue warning area over part of Cairns, which means
people should be aware the disease is right there and happening now.
The warning covers an area bordered by the world-famous Cairns waterfront,
one of the busiest streets in the city, and extending toward the
international airport.
A major television, radio and newspaper public awareness campaign also will
be launched to fight the outbreak.
A spokesman for Mayor Tom Pyne said the council had immediately gone on full
alert and that the city is fumigating every building and house along The
Esplanade. They are also asking residents to take action themselves.
In 1992-1993, 750 people were struck down in Townsville and Charters Towers
in Queensland's worst dengue episode.
The spokesman said recent warm and moist conditions in Cairns were ideal for
an outbreak.
--
Denis Green
Research and Development Director
