[I take it that the "1,000 north Queensland residents ... at risk of a
deadly form of dengue fever" is meant to indicate those people who were
infected during the 1992-93 epidemic and who might now be in danger of
acquiring a second dengue infection and therefore be at risk of developing
dengue hemorrhagic fever. If that is a correct read of the report, that
eventuality is not likely because most of those infected in the 1992-93
epidemic were adults. Nonetheless, this is a potentially serious situation
in which north Queensland, as are so many parts of the world, is becoming
hyperendemic for dengue.
This report reflects the obvious concern of local authorities. The Cairns
area is a tourist destination and this is not only the end of spring there
but the pre-Christmas season as well. People flock to north Queensland from
throughout Australia as well as from overseas, visiting from Mackay and
Townsville south of Cairns to the Cape York peninsula to the north and the
Great Barrier Reef islands. I am certain that the local authorities
including Scott Ritchie, the staff at James Cook University in Townsville,
and John Mackenzie and his staff at the University of Queensland will keep
us apprised of the situation as it develops. -- Mod CHC
...............................chc/es
